{"id":"1405.0908","submitter":"Nicolas Gautier","authors":"Nicolas Gautier, Thomas Duriez, Jean-Luc Aider, Bernd Noack, Marc\n  Segond, Markus Abel","title":"Closed-loop separation control using machine learning","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1017/jfm.2015.95","report-no":null,"categories":"physics.flu-dyn","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  A novel, model free, approach to experimental closed-loop flow control is\nimplemented on a separated flow. Feedback control laws are generated using\ngenetic programming where they are optimized using replication, mutation and\ncross-over of best performing laws to produce a new generation of candidate\ncontrol laws. This optimization process is applied automatically to a\nbackward-facing step flow at Re=1350, controlled by a slotted jet, yielding an\neffective control law. Convergence criterion are suggested. The law is able to\nproduce effective action even with major changes in the flow state,\ndemonstrating its robustness. The underlying physical mechanisms leveraged by\nthe law are analyzed and discussed. Contrary to traditional periodic forcing of\nthe shear layer, this new control law plays on the physics of the recirculation\narea downstream the step. While both control actions are fundamentally\ndifferent they still achieve the same level of effectiveness. Furthermore the\nnew law is also potentially easier and cheaper to implement actuator wise.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 5 May 2014 14:22:44 GMT"}],"update_date":"2015-06-19"}
